{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778560686,"nonce":"vKlhKH1682FQaY1zDTD3sb3ZiZk=","title":"Part of phase umbrella `f695729`. Follow-up from the `d448c9d` consultation synthesis (2026-05-11) — added per Codex's second-opinion pushback as Tier 0 (the cheapest and most decisive first check).","message":"Codex's second-opinion critique surfaced a load-bearing concern: we have been comparing GRU Δv ≈ -25% with linear Δv = +78% with analytical Riccati Δv = +1-27%, but these three numbers are **not cleanly comparable** unless plant, horizon, cost, adversary class, delay, task input, noise, and training objective all match. Most likely they do not. Before running any GRU representational analysis or building a real trajectory tracker, audit the observable differences across the existing checkpoints.\n\n\nFor each of the following four \"controllers\" (existing artifacts, no new training):\n\n1. **Baseline GRU** (e.g. the f47abb1 `lit__post_nojerk` winner, warmup-only)\n2. **Flavor-B adversarially-trained GRU** (e.g. from `c723082`)\n3. **Trained LTV linear regulator** from the corrected MVP (`410d7ac`, `linear_regulator__adversarial`)\n4. **Analytical H∞ Riccati** (from `src/rlrmp/analysis/hinf_riccati.py`)\n\nRun a single nominal forward simulation (no disturbance) and report:\n\n- Nominal movement time / peak forward velocity / terminal position error\n- State-cost time course `x_t^T Q_t x_t` over the trial\n- Control-cost time course `u_t^T R_t u_t` over the trial\n- The adversary loss actually optimized for each model (e.g. `LinearDynamicsAdversary` `ΔA` Frobenius-bounded vs full-state `B_w` additive) vs the Riccati `w → z` induced norm\n- Exact delay treatment (sensory delay channel, motor filter, hold period structure)\n- Exact noise treatment (motor noise, sensory noise, catch trials)\n- Exact task input structure (target_pos channel, target_vel, hold flag, target_on, SISU, etc.)\n- Loss term breakdown: which terms are active for the trained linear vs the trained GRU (effector_hold_pos, effector_pos_running, effector_vel_late, nn_output, nn_hidden, jerk, etc.)\n\n\nA single side-by-side comparison table / document at `results/d448c9d/notes/2026-05-11_trajectory_cost_audit.md` (or similar) with all the above quantities. Highlight any axis on which the four controllers differ — those axes are the prime suspects for the +78% vs +1-27% discrepancy.\n\n\n- **If the trained linear regulator and Riccati controller already differ on plant/horizon/cost/adversary in non-trivial ways**: the empirical Δv comparison is uninterpretable until those axes are aligned. Tier 1 (Riccati round-trip, `66a3374`) becomes the immediate next step.\n- **If they line up cleanly**: the +78% vs +1-27% discrepancy is a real mystery and Tier 1 stays critical. Continue.\n- **If the GRU has additional loss terms or task-input channels the linear regulator does not**: those couplings need to be stripped (or matched) before Tier 4 (`0083c5f`, GRU under matched objective) is interpretable.\n\n\nNone — uses existing artifacts only. Should take a couple of hours.\n\n\n- Parent: `d448c9d` (decoupling acid test)\n- Umbrella: `f695729` (regulator-coupling phase)\n- Consultation: `results/d448c9d/consultations/2026-05-11_decoupling_framing/` — see `codex_second_opinion.md` for the rationale\n- Blocks: Tier 1 / `66a3374` (`66a3374`'s 2.2 sub-item — Riccati round-trip — depends on knowing the actual cost/plant differences first)\n- Related: `4469cae` (eval-pipeline audit; some of the same hygiene concerns)","files":null}]}